subSubSection.paragraph:
Uropod (
Figure 7C
).

Sympod slightly longer than the endopod and four times longer than wide; with seven barbed spines of different size; endopod slightly shorter than exopod with two strong, barbed spines and one claw (
Figure 7D
) on the distal end and two plumose setae on the external part which exceed the distal end of the endopod, and two barbed terminal setae, four groups of ctenidia on dorsal face; exopod has two barbed terminal setae, the outer longer than the inner, and four barbed setae on external face.
